1. Why is it important to write clean code?
A:  Because it will be easier to understand in the future when you read it again , and also for your colleagues

2. What is the difference between good comments and bad comments?
A:Good comments explain the logic of the code, straight to the point, bad comments contain unnecessary information

3. What is an array?
A: A special variable, which can hold more than one value

4. What are arrays useful for?
A: To store a list of items

5. How do you access an array element?
A: arr[index]

6. How do you change an array element?
A: arr[index]=newvalue;

7. What are some useful array properties?
A: .length

8. What are some useful array methods?
A: .sort, .pop,.push,.shift

9. What are loops useful for?
A: To exectute a piece of code more times

10.What is the break statement?
A: The break statement exits the current iteration of a loop

11. What is the continue statement?
A: The loop statement skips the current iteration

12.What is the DOM?
A: A language-independent interface that treats an XML or HTML document as a tree structure

13.How do you target the nodes you want to work with?
A: using element.querySelector, .getElementbyId,etc

14.How do you create an element in the DOM?
A: document.createElement

15.How do you add an element to the DOM?
A: Using appendChild(childNode) , insertBefore(newNode, referenceNode) 

16.How do you remove an element from the DOM?
A: Using parentNode.removeChild(child) 

17.How can you alter an element in the DOM?
A: Using set.Attribute

18.When adding text to a DOM element, should you use textContent or innerHTML? 
A: textContent, it is more secure

19. Where should you include your JavaScript tag in your HTML file when working
with DOM nodes?
A:At the end of body tag

20.How do “events” and “listeners” work?
A: using .addEventListener / onclick

21.What are three ways to use events in your code?
A: inline, using a property, or using a listener

22.Why are event listeners the preferred way to handle events?
A: Because the code is easier to change in the future
           
23.What are the benefits of using named functions in your listeners?
A: helps keep your code more DRY 

24.How do you attach listeners to groups of nodes?
A: using .forEach

25. What is the difference between the return values of querySelector and
querySelectorAll?
A: querySelectorAll returns an array of value, querySelector return the first value with the certain condition

26.What does a “nodelist” contain?
A: all of the items matching a specific selector 

27.Explain the difference between “capture” and “bubbling”. 
A:
Bubbling: When an event happens on an element, it first runs the handlers on it, then on its parent, then all the way up on other ancestors.
Capture: The event is first captured by the outermost element and propagated to the inner elements.

28.What is the difference between objects and arrays? 
A: Objects represent “things” with characteristics, while arrays create and store lists of data in a single variable.

29.How do you access object properties?
A: obj[propertyname];
